{"title_page": "The Blue Notebooks", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Blue Notebooks\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Max Richter]]\n| cover      = The Blue Notebooks (Front Cover).png\n| alt        =\n| released   = 26 February 2004\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Eastcote Studios<br><small>([[London, England]])</small> <br/>Hear No Evil Studios<br><small>(London, England)</small>\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Contemporary classical music|Contemporary classical]]\n*[[Ambient Music|ambient]]\n}}\n| length     = 40:29\n| label      = [[FatCat Records|130701]]\n| producer   = Max Richter\n| prev_title = [[Memoryhouse (album)|Memoryhouse]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title = [[Songs from Before (Max Richter album)|Songs from Before]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = The Blue Notebooks (Front Cover) (Reissue).png\n | border  = yes\n | alt     =\n | caption = 2014 reissue cover\n}}\n}}\n'''''The Blue Notebooks''''' is the second [[album]] by British producer and composer [[Max Richter]], released on 26 February 2004 on 130701, an imprint of [[FatCat Records]].\n\nOn 11 May 2018, a two-disc version of ''The Blue Notebooks'' was reissued by [[Deutsche Grammophon]] to commemorate its fifteenth anniversary. It includes remixes by other artists, re-recordings, and two alternate arrangements of \"On the Nature of Daylight\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deutschegrammophon.com/us/cat/4835014 |title=RICHTER Blue Notebooks (15 Years Edition) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |publisher=Deutsche Grammophon |access-date=21 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://spectrumculture.com/2018/07/17/max-richter-the-blue-notebooks-15-years-edition-review/ |title=Max Richter: The Blue Notebooks (15 Years Edition) |last=Lockie |first=Connor |date=17 July 2018 |website=Spectrum Culture |access-date=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nRichter composed ''The Blue Notebooks'' in the run-up to the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]]. He has described it as \"a protest album about Iraq, a meditation on violence \u2013 both the violence that I had personally experienced around me as a child and the violence of war, at the utter futility of so much armed conflict.\" The album was recorded about a week after [[February 15, 2003, anti-war protests|mass protests against the war]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Richter|first1=Max|title=Millions of us knew the Iraq war would be a catastrophe. Why didn\u2019t Tony Blair?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jul/08/iraq-war-tony-blair-creativity-chilcot-inquiry|accessdate=8 July 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|date=8 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe album features readings from [[Franz Kafka]]'s ''[[The Blue Octavo Notebooks]]'' and [[Czes\u0142aw Mi\u0142osz]]'s ''Hymn of the Pearl'' and ''Unattainable Earth''. Both readings are by the British actress [[Tilda Swinton]].\n\n==Use in films and TV==\nThe tracks \"Shadow Journal\" and \"Organum\" were included in the soundtrack of the animated documentary ''[[Waltz with Bashir]]'' (2008).\n\n\"On the Nature of Daylight\" has been extensively used in cinema. It appeared in the 2006 [[Will Ferrell]] film ''[[Stranger than Fiction (2006 film)|Stranger than Fiction]]'', ''[[Disconnect (2012 film)|Disconnect]]'' (2012), directed by [[Henry Alex Rubin]], ''[[The Face of an Angel]]'' (2014), directed by [[Michael Winterbottom]], ''[[The Innocents (2016 film)|The Innocents]]'' (2016), directed by [[Anne Fontaine]], the documentary ''[[Jiro Dreams of Sushi]]'', directed by [[David Gelb]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.soundtrack.net/movie/jiro-dreams-of-sushi/ |title=Jiro Dreams of Sushi (2012) |work=Soundtrack.Net |access-date=2 October 2018 |publisher=Autotelics, LLC. |date=9 March 2012}}</ref> ''[[Arrival (film)|Arrival]]'' (2016), directed by [[Denis Villeneuve]], and ''[[Togo (film)|Togo]]'' (2019), directed by [[Ericson Core]]. It is also used on the soundtrack of [[Martin Scorsese]]'s 2010 film, ''[[Shutter Island (film)|Shutter Island]]'', in its original form and remixed with [[Dinah Washington]]'s vocals from her 1960 hit \"[[This Bitter Earth]]\". This remixed version was also used in the closing scenes of \"[[La French]]\" directed by [[C\u00e9dric Jimenez]]. It has also been used in the Hulu Original TV series ''[[Castle Rock (TV series)|Castle Rock]]'' during the ending scene of the episode \"The Queen\" following into the credits. The BBC used it for their coverage of the centenary of the [[Battle of the Somme]] in 2016. In 2019, it was used in a Korean TV series ''[[Dazzling (TV series)|Dazzling]]'' during the 11th episode. It was additionally used in both the opening and closing sequences of the 2016 film [[Arrival_(film)|''Arrival'']], the use of which disqualified the original score from contending for an [[Academy_Award_for_Best_Original_Score|Oscar]].<ref>{cite magazine |last=Tapley |first=Kristopher |title=Oscars: Academy Disqualifies 'Arrival,' 'Silence,' 'Manchester' Original Scores |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/in-contention/oscars-academy-disqualifies-arrival-manchester-by-the-sea-silence-1201941479/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=February 26, 2017 |date=December 13, 2016}}</ref> In 2020 the song appeared in the 35th anniversary of Eastenders. In 2020 the song also appeared in Episode 6 of the British sitcom [[The Trip To Greece]]. \n\nThe track \"Vladimir's Blues\" is featured throughout all three seasons of the TV series ''[[The Leftovers (TV series)|The Leftovers]]''.\n<ref>{{cite news |title='Shutter Island' soundtrack casts eerie spell |first=Bradley |last=Bambarger |url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/music/index.ssf/2010/03/shutter_island_soundtrack_cast.html |newspaper=[[New Jersey On-Line]] |date=12 March 2010 |access-date=19 December 2018 |publisher=Advance Local Media LLC.}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-blue-notebooks-mw0000808503 |title=The Blue Notebooks \u2013 Max Richter |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=5 July 2019 |first=Heather |last=Phares}}</ref>\n| rev2      = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev2score = 8.7/10<ref name=pitchfork>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/6917-the-blue-notebooks/ |title=Max Richter: The Blue Notebooks |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=1 July 2004 |access-date=21 November 2017 |first=Mark |last=Pytlik}}</ref>\n| rev3      = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev3score = 8/10<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.popmatters.com/192773-max-richter-the-blue-notebooks-2495537909.html |title=Max Richter: The Blue Notebooks |work=[[PopMatters]] |date=12 May 2015 |access-date=5 July 2019 |first=John |last=Garratt}}</ref>\n| rev4      = ''[[Resident Advisor]]''\n| rev4score = 4.5/5<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/reviews/22569 |title=Max Richter \u2013 The Blue Notebooks (15 Years Edition) |work=[[Resident Advisor]] |date=5 June 2018 |access-date=5 July 2019 |first=Holly |last=Dicker}}</ref>\n| rev5      = ''[[Stylus Magazine]]''\n| rev5score = B\u2212<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stylusmagazine.com/reviews/max-richter/the-blue-notebook.htm |title=Max Richter \u2013 The Blue Notebook \u2013 Review |work=[[Stylus Magazine]] |first=Ron |last=Schepper |date=10 March 2004 |access-date=19 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060901225819/http://www.stylusmagazine.com:80/reviews/max-richter/the-blue-notebook.htm |archive-date=1 September 2006}}</ref>\n| rev6      = ''[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]''\n| rev6score = 4/5<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/music-review/max-richter-blue-notebooks |title=Max Richter \u2013 The Blue Notebooks |work=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]] |access-date=5 July 2019 |author=Jean-Pierre}}</ref>\n| rev7      = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev7score = 8/10<ref>{{cite journal |title=Max Richter: The Blue Notebooks |work=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |issue=255 |date=August 2018 |first=Piers |last=Martin |page=45}}</ref>\n}}\n''The Blue Notebooks'' received widespread critical acclaim from contemporary music critics.\n\nMark Pytlik of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' gave the album a very positive review, explaining<blockquote>''The Blue Notebooks'' is a case study in direct, minor-key melody. Each of the piano pieces \"Horizon Variations\", \"Vladimir's Blues\" and \"Written on the Sky\" establish strong melodic motifs in under two minutes, all the while resisting additional orchestration. Elsewhere, Richter's string suites are similarly striking; \"On the Nature of Daylight\" coaxes a stunning rise out of gently provincial arrangements while the comparatively epic penultimate track \"The Trees\" boasts an extended introductory sequence for what is probably the album's closest brush with grandiosity.\n\n...\n\nRichter's slightly less traditional pieces also resound; both the underwater choral hymnal \"Iconography\" and the stately organ piece \"Organum\" echo the spiritual ambience that characterized his work for Future Sound of London. There is absolutely nothing exclusive or contrived-feeling about it. In fact, not only is Richter's second album one of the finest of the last six months, it is also one of the most affecting and universal contemporary classical records in recent memory.<ref name=\"pitchfork\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length    = 40:29\n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        = \n| all_writing     = Max Richter\n\n| title1          = The Blue Notebooks\n| length1          = 1:19\n\n| title2          = On the Nature of Daylight\n| length2          = 6:11\n\n| title3          = Horizon Variations\n| length3          = 1:52\n\n| title4          = Shadow Journal\n| length4          = 8:22\n\n| title5          = Iconography\n| length5          = 3:38\n\n| title6          = Vladimir's Blues\n| length6          = 1:18\n\n| title7          = Arboretum\n| length7          = 2:53\n\n| title8          = Old Song\n| length8          = 2:11\n\n| title9         = Organum\n| length9         = 3:13\n\n| title10         = The Trees\n| length10         = 7:52\n\n| title11         = Written on the Sky\n| length11          = 1:40\n}}\n\n== ''The Blue Notebooks: 15 Years Edition'' ==\nReleased in 2018 by [[Deutsche Grammophon]]. Includes seven bonus tracks.\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = Max Richter\n| title1 = \n| length1 = \n| title2 = \n| length2 = \n| title3 = \n| length3 = \n| title4 = \n| length4 = \n| title5 = \n| length5 = \n| title6 = \n| length6 = \n| title7 = \n| length7 = \n| title8 = \n| length8 = \n| title9 = \n| length9 = \n| title10 = \n| length10 = \n| title11 = \n| length11 = \n| title12 = A Catalogue of Afternoons\n| length12 = 1:21\n| title13 = On the Nature of Daylight (Orchestral Version)\n| length13 = 6:36\n| title14 = Vladimir's Blues 2018\n| length14 = 1:30\n| title15 = On the Nature of Daylight (Entropy)\n| length15 = 6:54\n| title16 = Vladimir's Blues (Jlin Remix)\n| length16 = 3:45\n| title17 = Iconography (Konx-Om-Pax Remix)\n| length17 = 3:56\n| title18 = This Bitter Earth / On the Nature Of Daylight w/ Dinah Washington\n| length18 = 6:13\n| title19 = \n| length19 = \n| title20 = \n| length20 = \n| total_length = \n}}\n\n* Track 1 reading from \"The First Notebook\" in Franz Kafka's ''The Blue Octavo Notebooks''\n* Track 4 reading from \"At Dawn\" in Czes\u0142aw Mi\u0142osz's ''Unattainable Earth''\n* Track 7 reading from \"The Third Notebook\" in Franz Kafka's ''The Blue Octavo Notebooks''\n* Track 8 reading from \"The Fourth Notebook\" in Franz Kafka's ''The Blue Octavo Notebooks''\n* Track 10 reading from \"The Wormwood Star\" movement of \"The Separate Notebooks\" in Czes\u0142aw Mi\u0142osz's ''Hymn Of The Pearl''\n\n== Personnel ==\nCredits adapted from ''The Blue Notebooks: 15 Years Edition'' interior booklet:<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nReader: Tilda Swinton (1, 4, 7, 8, 10)\n\nPiano: Max Richter (1, 3, 6, 8, 10, 11, 12, 14-16)\n\nElectronics: Max Richter (1, 3-5, 7-10, 17)\n\nViolins: Louisa Fuller and Natalia Bonner (2, 4, 7, 10, 15, 18)\n\nViola: John Metcalfe (2, 4, 7, 10, 15, 18)\n\nCellos: Philip Sheppard and Chris Worsey (2, 4, 7, 10, 18); Chris Worsey and Ian Burdge (15)\n\nMax Richter Orchestra conducted by Lorenz Dangel (13)\n\nVocals: Dinah Washington (18)\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Country\n! Date\n|-\n| [[United Kingdom]]\n| 26 February 2004\n|-\n| [[United States]]\n| 18 May 2004\n|-\n|[[United States]]\n|11 May 2018\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* ''[http://fat-cat.co.uk/fatcat/release.php?id=101 The Blue Notebooks]'' at Fat Cat\n* \"[http://artistxite.com/us/album/1330585/The-Blue-Notebooks.html Essential Listening: The Blue Notebooks]\u201c at artistxite\n* [http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/4148277-max-richter-on-the-blue-notebooks--a-10th-anniversary-track-by-track-guide Track by track guide to The Blue Notebooks] at Drowned In Sound\n\n{{Max Richter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blue Notebooks}}\n[[Category:2004 albums]]\n[[Category:Max Richter albums]]\n[[Category:FatCat Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Blue Notebooks\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Max Richter]]\n| cover      = The Blue Notebooks (Front Cover).png\n| alt        =\n| released   = 26 February 2004\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Eastcote Studios<br><small>([[London, England]])</small> <br/>Hear No Evil Studios<br><small>(London, England)</small>\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Contemporary classical music|Contemporary classical]]\n*[[Ambient Music|ambient]]\n}}\n| length     = 40:29\n| label      = [[FatCat Records|130701]]\n| producer   = Max Richter\n| prev_title = [[Memoryhouse (album)|Memoryhouse]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title = [[Songs from Before (Max Richter album)|Songs from Before]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = The Blue Notebooks (Front Cover) (Reissue).png\n | border  = yes\n | alt     =\n | caption = 2014 reissue cover\n}}\n}}\n'''''The Blue Notebooks''''' is the second [[album]] by British producer and composer [[Max Richter]], released on 26 February 2004 on 130701, an imprint of [[FatCat Records]].\n\nOn 11 May 2018, a two-disc version of ''The Blue Notebooks'' was reissued by [[Deutsche Grammophon]] to commemorate its fifteenth anniversary. It includes remixes by other artists, re-recordings, and two alternate arrangements of \"On the Nature of Daylight\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deutschegrammophon.com/us/cat/4835014 |title=RICHTER Blue Notebooks (15 Years Edition) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |publisher=Deutsche Grammophon |access-date=21 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://spectrumculture.com/2018/07/17/max-richter-the-blue-notebooks-15-years-edition-review/ |title=Max Richter: The Blue Notebooks (15 Years Edition) |last=Lockie |first=Connor |date=17 July 2018 |website=Spectrum Culture |access-date=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nRichter composed ''The Blue Notebooks'' in the run-up to the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]]. He has described it as \"a protest album about Iraq, a meditation on violence \u2013 both the violence that I had personally experienced around me as a child and the violence of war, at the utter futility of so much armed conflict.\" The album was recorded about a week after [[February 15, 2003, anti-war protests|mass protests against the war]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Richter|first1=Max|title=Millions of us knew the Iraq war would be a catastrophe. Why didn\u2019t Tony Blair?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jul/08/iraq-war-tony-blair-creativity-chilcot-inquiry|accessdate=8 July 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|date=8 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe album features readings from [[Franz Kafka]]'s ''[[The Blue Octavo Notebooks]]'' and [[Czes\u0142aw Mi\u0142osz]]'s ''Hymn of the Pearl'' and ''Unattainable Earth''. Both readings are by the British actress [[Tilda Swinton]].\n\n==Use in films and TV==\nThe tracks \"Shadow Journal\" and \"Organum\" were included in the soundtrack of the animated documentary ''[[Waltz with Bashir]]'' (2008).\n\n\"On the Nature of Daylight\" has been extensively used in cinema. It appeared in the 2006 [[Will Ferrell]] film ''[[Stranger than Fiction (2006 film)|Stranger than Fiction]]'', ''[[Disconnect (2012 film)|Disconnect]]'' (2012), directed by [[Henry Alex Rubin]], ''[[The Face of an Angel]]'' (2014), directed by [[Michael Winterbottom]], ''[[The Innocents (2016 film)|The Innocents]]'' (2016), directed by [[Anne Fontaine]], the documentary ''[[Jiro Dreams of Sushi]]'', directed by [[David Gelb]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.soundtrack.net/movie/jiro-dreams-of-sushi/ |title=Jiro Dreams of Sushi (2012) |work=Soundtrack.Net |access-date=2 October 2018 |publisher=Autotelics, LLC. |date=9 March 2012}}</ref>, ''[[Arrival (film)|Arrival]]'' (2016), directed by [[Denis Villeneuve]], and ''[[Togo (film)|Togo]]'' (2019), directed by [[Ericson Core]]. It is also used on the soundtrack of [[Martin Scorsese]]'s 2010 film, ''[[Shutter Island (film)|Shutter Island]]'', in its original form and remixed with [[Dinah Washington]]'s vocals from her 1960 hit \"[[This Bitter Earth]]\". This remixed version was also used in the closing scenes of \"[[La French]]\" directed by [[C\u00e9dric Jimenez]]. It has also been used in the Hulu Original TV series ''[[Castle Rock (TV series)|Castle Rock]]'' during the ending scene of the episode \"The Queen\" following into the credits. The BBC used it for their coverage of the centenary of the [[Battle of the Somme]] in 2016. In 2019, it was used in a Korean TV series ''[[Dazzling (TV series)|Dazzling]]'' during the 11th episode. It was additionally used in both the opening and closing sequences of the 2016 film [[Arrival_(film)|''Arrival'']], the use of which disqualified the original score from contending for an [[Academy_Award_for_Best_Original_Score|Oscar]].<ref>{cite magazine |last=Tapley |first=Kristopher |title=Oscars: Academy Disqualifies 'Arrival,' 'Silence,' 'Manchester' Original Scores |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/in-contention/oscars-academy-disqualifies-arrival-manchester-by-the-sea-silence-1201941479/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=February 26, 2017 |date=December 13, 2016}}</ref> In 2020 the song appeared in the 35th anniversary of Eastenders. In 2020 the song also appeared in Episode 6 of the British sitcom [[The Trip To Greece]]. \n\nThe track \"Vladimir's Blues\" is featured throughout all three seasons of the TV series ''[[The Leftovers (TV series)|The Leftovers]]''.\n<ref>{{cite news |title='Shutter Island' soundtrack casts eerie spell |first=Bradley |last=Bambarger |url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/music/index.ssf/2010/03/shutter_island_soundtrack_cast.html |newspaper=[[New Jersey On-Line]] |date=12 March 2010 |access-date=19 December 2018 |publisher=Advance Local Media LLC.}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-blue-notebooks-mw0000808503 |title=The Blue Notebooks \u2013 Max Richter |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=5 July 2019 |first=Heather |last=Phares}}</ref>\n| rev2      = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev2score = 8.7/10<ref name=pitchfork>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/6917-the-blue-notebooks/ |title=Max Richter: The Blue Notebooks |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=1 July 2004 |access-date=21 November 2017 |first=Mark |last=Pytlik}}</ref>\n| rev3      = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev3score = 8/10<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.popmatters.com/192773-max-richter-the-blue-notebooks-2495537909.html |title=Max Richter: The Blue Notebooks |work=[[PopMatters]] |date=12 May 2015 |access-date=5 July 2019 |first=John |last=Garratt}}</ref>\n| rev4      = ''[[Resident Advisor]]''\n| rev4score = 4.5/5<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/reviews/22569 |title=Max Richter \u2013 The Blue Notebooks (15 Years Edition) |work=[[Resident Advisor]] |date=5 June 2018 |access-date=5 July 2019 |first=Holly |last=Dicker}}</ref>\n| rev5      = ''[[Stylus Magazine]]''\n| rev5score = B\u2212<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stylusmagazine.com/reviews/max-richter/the-blue-notebook.htm |title=Max Richter \u2013 The Blue Notebook \u2013 Review |work=[[Stylus Magazine]] |first=Ron |last=Schepper |date=10 March 2004 |access-date=19 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060901225819/http://www.stylusmagazine.com:80/reviews/max-richter/the-blue-notebook.htm |archive-date=1 September 2006}}</ref>\n| rev6      = ''[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]''\n| rev6score = 4/5<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/music-review/max-richter-blue-notebooks |title=Max Richter \u2013 The Blue Notebooks |work=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]] |access-date=5 July 2019 |author=Jean-Pierre}}</ref>\n| rev7      = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev7score = 8/10<ref>{{cite journal |title=Max Richter: The Blue Notebooks |work=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |issue=255 |date=August 2018 |first=Piers |last=Martin |page=45}}</ref>\n}}\n''The Blue Notebooks'' received widespread critical acclaim from contemporary music critics.\n\nMark Pytlik of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' gave the album a very positive review, explaining<blockquote>''The Blue Notebooks'' is a case study in direct, minor-key melody. Each of the piano pieces \"Horizon Variations\", \"Vladimir's Blues\" and \"Written on the Sky\" establish strong melodic motifs in under two minutes, all the while resisting additional orchestration. Elsewhere, Richter's string suites are similarly striking; \"On the Nature of Daylight\" coaxes a stunning rise out of gently provincial arrangements while the comparatively epic penultimate track \"The Trees\" boasts an extended introductory sequence for what is probably the album's closest brush with grandiosity.\n\n...\n\nRichter's slightly less traditional pieces also resound; both the underwater choral hymnal \"Iconography\" and the stately organ piece \"Organum\" echo the spiritual ambience that characterized his work for Future Sound of London. There is absolutely nothing exclusive or contrived-feeling about it. In fact, not only is Richter's second album one of the finest of the last six months, it is also one of the most affecting and universal contemporary classical records in recent memory.<ref name=\"pitchfork\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length    = 40:29\n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        = \n| all_writing     = Max Richter\n\n| title1          = The Blue Notebooks\n| length1          = 1:19\n\n| title2          = On the Nature of Daylight\n| length2          = 6:11\n\n| title3          = Horizon Variations\n| length3          = 1:52\n\n| title4          = Shadow Journal\n| length4          = 8:22\n\n| title5          = Iconography\n| length5          = 3:38\n\n| title6          = Vladimir's Blues\n| length6          = 1:18\n\n| title7          = Arboretum\n| length7          = 2:53\n\n| title8          = Old Song\n| length8          = 2:11\n\n| title9         = Organum\n| length9         = 3:13\n\n| title10         = The Trees\n| length10         = 7:52\n\n| title11         = Written on the Sky\n| length11          = 1:40\n}}\n\n== ''The Blue Notebooks: 15 Years Edition'' ==\nReleased in 2018 by [[Deutsche Grammophon]]. Includes seven bonus tracks.\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = Max Richter\n| title1 = \n| length1 = \n| title2 = \n| length2 = \n| title3 = \n| length3 = \n| title4 = \n| length4 = \n| title5 = \n| length5 = \n| title6 = \n| length6 = \n| title7 = \n| length7 = \n| title8 = \n| length8 = \n| title9 = \n